# Intuition
We have an array `arr` where two consecutive elements can be either one of these:-
1. `arr[i] > arr[i-1]`
2. `arr[i] < arr[i-1]`
3. `arr[i] == arr[i-1]` `Apparently arr[i] not a part of the mountain array`
Looking at our question carefully, we can say for cases with `arr.size() < 3` would  have no mountain array. Whenever the array is increasing first(i.e. 1st condition holds first) there is a possibility of having the required array.But we can't be assured until we encounter 2nd condition at least once. This is the primary logic behind.

# Approach
We initialise two variables to check when our array is strictly increasing or strictly decreasing. Next we check the cases where the monotonocity is broken.Cases where 3rd condition mentioned in intuition hold will just be ignored and thus we approach the maximum length of mountain we can encounter.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N)
- Space complexity:
O(1)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int longestMountain(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
// no mountain exists
        if(n < 3) return 0;
        int ans = 0,temp = 0,checkinc = 0, checkdec = 0;
        for(int  i = 1; i < n; i++){
            if(arr[i] > arr[i-1]){
// the end of the mountain
                if(checkdec == 1){
                    ans = max(temp,ans);
                    checkdec = 0;
                    checkinc = 1;
                    temp = 2;
                }
                else{
// the start of a new mountain
                    if(checkinc == 0){
                    temp =2;
                    checkinc = 1;
                    }
//add to the existing mountain
                    else
                    temp++;
                }
            }
            else if(arr[i] < arr[i-1]){
// the peak of the mountain
                if(checkinc == 1){
                    if(checkdec == 0)
                    checkdec =1;
//add to the existing mountain
                    temp++;
                }
//no mountain
                else{
                temp = 0;
                checkdec = 0;
                checkinc = 0;
            }
            }
            else{
// the end of the mountain
                if(checkinc == 1 && checkdec == 1)
                 ans = max(temp,ans);
// no mountain exists here
                 checkinc = 0;
                 checkdec = 0;
                 temp = 0;
            }
        }
// the end of the mountain
        if(checkinc == 1 && checkdec == 1)
        ans = max(temp,ans);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

