The first approach came to mind immediately is expand from center, which will go to O(n^2).
After sumbitting I realized that there has to be an O(n) solution.
## Linear Scan, O(n)
I view a mountain as left-top-right.
```
    public int longestMountain(int[] arr) {
        int ans = 0;
        int left = 0;
        while (left < arr.length - 2) {
            int top = left;
            while (top + 1 < arr.length && arr[top + 1] > arr[top]) top++;
            int right = top;
            while (right + 1 < arr.length && arr[right + 1] < arr[right]) right++;
            if (left < top && top < right) ans = Math.max(ans, right - left + 1);
            left = Math.max(left + 1, right);
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

## Expand From Center, O(n^2)
```
    public int longestMountain(int[] arr) {
        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) ans = Math.max(ans, expandFromCenter(i, arr));
        return ans;
    }

    private int expandFromCenter(int center, int[] a) {
        int left = center;
        int right = center;
        while (left - 1 >= 0 && a[left - 1] < a[left]) left--;
        while (right + 1 < a.length && a[right + 1] < a[right]) right++;
        return left == center || right == center ? 0 : right - left + 1;
    }
