```
 public int longestMountain(int[] array) {
        int longestLength = 0;
        int i = 1;
        while(i < array.length - 1){
            boolean isPeak = array[i - 1] < array[i] && array[i] > array[i + 1];

            if(!isPeak){
                i++;
                continue;
            }

            int leftIdx = i - 2;
            while(leftIdx >=0 && array[leftIdx] < array[leftIdx + 1]){
                leftIdx--;
            }

            int rightIdx = i + 2;
            while(rightIdx < array.length && array[rightIdx - 1] > array[rightIdx]){
                rightIdx++;
            }

            int currentLength = rightIdx - leftIdx - 1;
            if(currentLength > longestLength){
                longestLength = currentLength;
            }
            i = rightIdx;
        }
        return longestLength;
    }
```


**Intuition**:
First you have to know if a number is a peak. Once you know the peak you need to expand to its both directions and calulate its length along the way. Keep updating the length by comparing it with length of other peaks and choose the longest length.


**Algorithm**:
So we first have to know if the current number is the peak. Start traversing the array from left to right. If a current value satisfies the peak condition then store the boolean result in a variable call it 'isPeak'. Note that traversal will start from the second element, because it doesnt make sense to check if the first element is a peak, because it cant be, according to the definition of a peak.

Condition: array[ i - 1 ] < array[ i ] && array[ i ] > array[ i + 1 ]

The reason to use a boolean variable is just for simplying the code. Otherwise you can directly write a peak condition inside the if construct.

Lets move on, 

If the current value is not a peak then we dont do anything in this iteration, simply increment the iterator 'i' and just continue with the search for a peak on to the next element.

If we have the peak:
Then we have to expand to the right and left, so long as we have strictly decreasing integers in either directions.

**Lets expand to the left first:**
We already know the left( i - 1 ) of the current element (i) is smaller. So we dont have to check that again. We start from i - 2. Hence we define a variable leftIdx initialized to i - 2

Now we iterate through the left part backwords. As long as our leftIdx is in the bounds and array[leftIdx] < array[leftIdx + 1] . Keep decrementing the leftIdx. So that we can keep checking all values to the left. At the end leftIdx, will hold the index of the element from where the peak began.


**Lets expand to the right now:**
We already know that the right ( i + 1 ) of the current element ( i ) is greater. So we dont have to check that again. We start from i + 2

Now iterate through the right part forwards. As long as our rightIdx is in the bounds and array[ rightIdx - 1 ]  >  array[ i ]. Keep increamenting the rightIdx.  So that we can keep checking all values to the right. At the end rightIdx, will hold the index of the element to where the peak ends.

Now get the currentPeakLength by doing rightIdx - leftIdx - 1 
And compare it with the longestPeakLength,  and return the longest amongst them.


To increment the iteration variable i, do this:
i = rightIdx

Why it works ?. The rightIdx holds the location of a and end of a peak. All the element between a peak and this rightIdx, were in a strictly decreasing manner. So it doesnt make a sense to check values before the rightIdx.


**Complexity Analysis**

Time: O(n), How many times do we visit every element in the array ? There are few cases to consider. Lets say you have strictly increasing or strictly decreasing or a flat array. Then there is no peak. In all these three cases you visit each element once. But when we find a peak, we have to expand to left and right. There can be multiple peaks to expand. All these expansion is also a visit. So in this case too we are visiting each element for once at least. And then we visit every element at most 2-3 times. It converges to O(N)

