solutions.content:
The intuition is that since we only care about 26 letters, we can simply use an integer as a set.
If we take bitwise and between two integers, we will get 0 if there is no duplicate.
Also, we can just use bitwise OR to combine the previous strings. 
By this trick, we can avoid string add operation as well as faster inquiry for if all characters in current string is unique. 
```
class Solution {
    public int maxLength(List<String> arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        int[] ans = new int[1];
        int[][] bitMap = new int[n][2];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            int a = 0;
            for (char ch: arr.get(i).toCharArray()) {
                int bit = ch - 'a';
                if (((a >> bit) & 1) == 1) {
                    a = 0;
                    break;
                }
                a |= (1 << bit);
            }
            bitMap[i][0] = a;
            bitMap[i][1] = a == 0 ? 0 : arr.get(i).length();
        }
        dfs(arr, bitMap, ans, 0, 0, 0);
        return ans[0];
    }

    private void dfs(List<String> arr, int[][] bitMap, int[] ans, int start, int curLen, int curBit) {
        if (ans[0] < curLen) ans[0] = curLen;
        for (int i = start; i < arr.size(); ++i) {
            if ((curBit & bitMap[i][0]) != 0) continue;
            dfs(arr, bitMap, ans, i + 1, curLen + bitMap[i][1], curBit | bitMap[i][0]);
        }
    }
}
```

